But I doe rather expound it by way of enlargement of their Iuridicall authoritie: for insomuch as there are not in it any words prohibitorie touching the former manner of proceeding;

 and the scope of this Law, is to have those offenders convicted by other meanes than by order of Law, as they were before; I gather thereby, that the Statute giveth an additament of this sort: (viz.) That whereas before-time the King and the Lords of his Councell did not admit any Complaint, but such onely as carried within it a reasonable surmise of maintenance of their Iurisdiction; for the proofe whereof, also the Plaintife ought by the Statute 15. Hen. 6. cap. 4. to give Sureties, as I have before shewed. Now by this new Statute, over and besides that ancient authoritie, onely these three of the Councell, (viz.) the Chancellor, Treasurer, and Keeper of the Privie Seale (using the assistance of some others thereunto appointed) were enabled to heare & determine ordinarily of these 8. offences, and that without any manner of such suggestion, or

 surmise at all: And that both King Henry the seventh, and King Henry the eight, did many yeeres after the making of this Statute, sometime in person, and very often by their Councell, practise that by former Iurisdictions in the Star-Chamber, without any help of this new Law & Statute, it doth most certainly appeare by the Bookes of Entries kept there; which is a true Ephemeris or Iournall of the Acts of the Court.
